	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Memblers</b> [ Tue Jun 13, 2006 6:30 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">cartridge wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Also on the nesdev site, there are some roms that include a "source code"... is that compatable with 6502asm?</div>
<br />
<br />Not without some changes, a lot of assembler programs work differently (often in minor ways like the name/abbreviation of a command, sometimes not).  View the source to a programs here and it probably says what assembler it uses, if it doesn't say, ask here.
<br />
<br />Unfortunately there's not a standard assembler that everyone in NES development uses.  Here's what a lot of demos/games on here use:
<br />
<br />DASM: some older stuff uses this, Chris Covell's releases, good and easy to use except for the lack of an .incbin command.
<br />x816: old, needs win9x or DOSbox to run.  good assembler otherwise, though not a lot of source-released stuff uses it.
<br />NESasm/Magickit: a lot of people started with this one (including me), and it has some annoying bugs like not reporting some errors.  But it'll generate iNES headers to make .NES files at least..
<br />cc65: it's good, it's what I use, it has a learning curve but a lot of advanced features.
<br />wla-dx: looks good, also looks like it has a bit of a learning curve too.
<br />There's a bunch more besides those too.
<br />
<br />
<br />As for putting other characters in different games, the easy is to exchange the tiles and modify the palette (no programming needed).  But if the sprites are different sizes it would be very hard to do.  They'll definitely have different animations, so it'd look a little weird and I dunno about modifying a game's animation data (could be hard or easy, sounds like a pain though).  I hacked the princess from SMB2 into SMB1, and that was pretty easy.  Just by replacing the tiles and changing the palette.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


